Certainly! Here's an example of how you can generate a Pug (formerly known as Jade) form with an array of checkboxes and two numeric inputs:

1. **Install Pug**:
   If you haven't already, you need to install the Pug package:

   ```bash
   npm install pug
   ```

2. **Create Pug Template**:
   Create a Pug template file (e.g., `form.pug`) with the following content:

```pug
html
  head
    title Checkbox and Numeric Inputs Form
  body
    h1 Checkbox and Numeric Inputs Form
    form(action="/submit" method="post")
      h2 Checkbox List
      each item in checkboxItems
        label
          input(type="checkbox" name="checkbox" value=item)
          | #{item}
        br

      h2 Numeric Inputs
      label(for="numericInput1") Numeric Input 1:
      input(type="number" name="numericInput1" id="numericInput1")

      label(for="numericInput2") Numeric Input 2:
      input(type="number" name="numericInput2" id="numericInput2")

      button(type="submit") Submit
```

3. **Create Express.js Server**:
   Set up an Express.js server to render the Pug template and handle form submissions. Create a file (e.g., `app.js`) with the following code:

```javascript
const express = require('express');
const bodyParser = require('body-parser');
const app = express();

// Parse incoming request bodies
app.use(bodyParser.urlencoded({ extended: false }));

// Serve static files (CSS, JS, etc.)
app.use(express.static('public'));

// Sample data for checkbox items
const checkboxItems = ['Item 1', 'Item 2', 'Item 3'];

// Define route to render the form
app.get('/', (req, res) => {
  res.render('form', { checkboxItems });
});

// Handle form submission
app.post('/submit', (req, res) => {
  const selectedCheckboxes = req.body.checkbox || [];
  const numericInput1 = req.body.numericInput1 || 0;
  const numericInput2 = req.body.numericInput2 || 0;

  // Do something with the form data
  console.log('Selected Checkboxes:', selectedCheckboxes);
  console.log('Numeric Input 1:', numericInput1);
  console.log('Numeric Input 2:', numericInput2);

  res.redirect('/');
});

app.set('view engine', 'pug');

app.listen(3000, () => {
  console.log('Server is running on port 3000');
});
```

4. **Run the Server**:
   Run the server using Node.js:

```bash
node app.js
```

Visit `http://localhost:3000` in your browser to see the generated form.

In this example, we've created a Pug template with a checkbox list and two numeric inputs. The Express.js server renders the Pug template, handles form submissions, and logs the form data to the console.

Please note that this is a simple example, and you can customize it further to meet your specific requirements.

